        </head><body><article><h1 class="rm-manual">'Not sad that he got greased': Army veteran celebrates killing of Soleimani</h1>
<p class="rm-manual"> by <a href="https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/author/zachary-halaschak">Zachary Halaschak</a> </p>
<p class="rm-manual"> | January 03, 2020 12:55 PM </p>
<p><span>A</span> Gulf War veteran and journalist said that he was not upset “a damn bit” that the United States <a href="https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/irans-infamous-shadow-general-qassem-soleimani-killed-in-air-strike">killed Qassem Soleimani</a>. </p>
<p>Mike Glenn, a reporter for the Washington Times who served as an 
officer during the Gulf War, condemned Soleimani and his attacks on the 
United States in a viral tweet on Friday. </p>
<p>“I'm a reporter but I was a Soldier for several years and led a 
platoon of cavalry troops into combat in Iraq,” Glenn said. “Qassim 
Solemani was directly responsible for the deaths of scores of American 
military personnel in Iraq. </p>
<p>“I'm not sad that he got greased. Not a damn bit,” Glenn added. </p>
